blog.description: I probably read too many comics. Here are some highlights. If you like, go give money to the creators.

summary: A change of pace in an issue that is a change of pace itself is great way to have fun with a book. Focusing more on Miles...
body:
A change of pace in an issue that is a change of pace itself is great way to have fun with a book. Focusing more on Miles Morales than Spider-Man, this is a nice character issue, with Miles’s school life and friends (and an attempt by all of them to avoid said school life and go enjoy a hip hop exhibition) to the fore, rather than super-heroics. Although of course there is room for some super-heroism, don’t worry.

This two page spread of the group trying to get back to the school before they get busted is fun- against a background of the relevant transit lines, our little manga style characters make their way across the city, narrowly avoiding getting busted, with key moments depicted in the style of the rest of the issue featuring as flag pins or call out boxes. It’s a great way to depict a sequence that is little more than a comedy caper (no life threatening villainy here!), and the absence of dialogue increases the sense of slapstick so that it works even better than if it had been a more traditional wise-cracking Spidey sequence.

It’s yet another sign- if one was still needed- that Miles is in good hands after Bendis left for the Distinguished Competition.

From Miles Morales: Spider-Man 4, by Saladin Ahmed, Javier Garrón, David Curiel & Cory Petit

summary: theoriginalliamjones replied to your post “also, since all i've done this gross weekend is read comics, can...” (I have a theory...
body:
theoriginalliamjones replied to your post “also, since all i’ve done this gross weekend is read comics, can…”

(I have a theory that is is an accepted retcon. Because he was in highschool for like twenty years, so people decided it made more sense to say he was younger when he got his powers. Because there is even less of a chance he could have had as many highschool Spidey adventures if it was already senior year.)

ok lol i have too many uhhghhghhghhghhg for a mere reply but like i think he graduates in #28 and  starts uni in #31 which like…isn’t really that long considering…wtf asm is up to something in the 800s now? and there’s the whole vaaaaaaaaague marvel sliding scale of 4 publication years = about 1 actual year, and 31 was published just about 2 years after #1? i think the first time it’s explicitly said it’s his senior year is in issue #8! and like…two years def didn’t pass btw amazing fantasy #15 and asm #1?

haha this is totally gonna be my little nitpick hill to die on bc it’s such a stupid ass retcon, bc it’s like…so consistently mentioned that he’s a senior in those first 30 issues! he talks about affording uni, scholarships, visiting professors coming to his classes – and then even in the untold tales interstitial ones from the 90s, they have him visiting ESU (btw ASM #23 and #24). and betty brant is supposed to be a year younger than him but she left school to take care of her mother, and wtf that would make her freaking 14 when we first start the series!?

it’s so funny bc i don’t actually give a shit about all the continuity issues that i know comics bring (forged in the ouat fire heyyooo – lol if you take in all of the interstitial comics uncle ben has like 84 funerals) but like…THIS BOTHERS ME A LOT bc it just seems so fucking off the wall to just change this one particular thing? like…why??? and why is it just universally accepted? IT’S WEIRD OK.
